Since I read once that taking photographs of North Korean statues from behind is forbidden (some sort of cultural thing), I have made it a point to always go and look at the backs of statues, especially ones that are hard to access/not meant to be seen. LOTS of ppl poop there.

These are liminal spaces, always feels wrong/forbidden to go there, you are inverting the purpose of the statue, it was not designed to be looked at from behind. Try it, go and stay behind the back of a local statue for a few minutes, you too will feel it. Disturbing, intriguing.

The "sein" as a moment-eternity has always been a bit weird to me, because it is also on a lingual level associated with change. In the past tense verbs are combined with it if they portray change, and with "having" if they do not.

To a non-native English speaker, Gerund forms are definitely associated with continuity though, even when it is used as a noun.

An interesting fact is that in Slavic languages, "being" - –±–∏—Ç–∏–µ, is also the name of Genesis, and is also associated with the "everyday", the material

It most definitely is. Except people who have studied English grammar on an above-highschool level, no one really understands the language properly. From the Americans I have met in real life, no one knew when to properly use different past tenses, verb forms etc.

German is definitely the most philosophical language, with Slavic a close second. Generally I feel that the purer the tongue, the more meaning is revealed, and English nowadays is very much contaminated with Latin, French, etc.

One of the greatest pleasures of life is realizing you're wrong about the time and it actually being earlier than you think. Spent today thinking it's the second day of february, it's actually the first. Feeling ecstatic. A whole, brand new day, has been gifted to me.

In highschool I used to put my clock one hour forwards and every time I saw it I remembered in actuality I had an extra hour and was immediately hit by a burst of dopamine. Every single time I looked at that clock I felt energized. It was like a dopamine loophole that I found...
